column1: Data Supplied By: National Livestock Reporting Service
Data source: National Livestock Reporting Service
Please see terms of use here: https://www.mla.com.au/general/Terms-and-conditions/data-and-information/

Numbers were steady and the quality was back with more breed related changes and fewer prime grown cattle. Feeder were still strong on yearlings and were going after more condition. There were good lines of heavy cows. Feeders were cheaper as were cows but prime heavy weight grown cattle were dearer.
 
The best price for butcher vealers reached 328c/kg. Yearling feeder steers were 8c to 12c cheaper on the medium weight runs with the bulk ranging from 318c to 359c/kg. Heavy weights dropped 20c with most ranging from 316c to 350c/kg and heavy export feeders were firm to 3c softer selling from 274c to 316c/kg. Heavy trade steers and heifers were firm to 5c easier with steers 306c to 367c and heifers reached 348c/kg.
 
Prime grown steers and bullocks were 10c stronger selling from 315c to 367c and heavy grown heifers also lifted 10c with most 320c top 350c/kg. Heavy cows were 3c to 4c softer selling from 265c to 300c/kg and the medium weight 2 score cows dropped 20c with no restocking activity 190c to 245c/kg. Bulls were 15c stronger on the medium weights and firm on heavy bulls.
